    <title>Combined summary - Warning: many 0.7 nodes break on large number of tx/block; fork risk</title>
    <updated>2023-06-06T10:52:41.306926+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-March/002236.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In March 2013, there were multiple issues with Bitcoin nodes that required immediate attention. One of these issues was related to lock exhaustion in BDB on some 0.7 nodes, causing transactions to stack up in the memory pool and leading to nodes dying with OOM failures. The lack of bounds on the memory pool size in Bitcoin could cause most users who don't fully understand the system to experience problems. Two alternatives were suggested - blocking or down-prioritizing SatoshiDice transactions at the network level or performing a crash hard fork as soon as possible, potentially lifting the 1mb limit at the same time. Another issue was related to lock entries in the BDB database that caused some 0.7 nodes to get stuck around block 225430. Upgrading to 0.8 or manually setting the number of lock objects higher in the database were suggested as immediate solutions. Despite these issues, there was a move towards self-reliance in the Bitcoin network. End-users have been able to relay their own transactions for some time, but recent developments have made it more difficult for these users to get their transactions confirmed.The context emphasizes the importance of maintaining a continuous loop of nodes and taking proactive measures to prevent node death or hard forks. The proper functioning of nodes is essential for the smooth operation of the network. Mike Hearn proposed implementing a "while [ true ] do ; ./bitcoind ; done" loop combined with ulimit to keep total memory usage to something sane as a temporary solution until proper mempool code with expiration could be written.The context also discusses the need for more space in blocks and proper handling of mem-pool transactions. Mempools are relatively small in memory usage but could risk going up with small block sizes. It was proposed to prune mempool transactions based on two criteria: if they are too old (&gt;24hr) or when the client is running out of space, then the oldest should probably be pruned. Clients keep and re-relay their own transactions; hence dropping free/old transactions would be a much better behavior than dying.In addition, the context highlights the significance of maintaining a continuous loop of nodes and taking proactive measures to prevent node death or hard forks. It emphasizes the importance of immediate action to avoid any possible negative consequences. The proper functioning of nodes is essential for the smooth operation of the network, and any negligence in this regard can cause severe damage to the network.On March 12, 2013, Bitcoin nodes experienced an emergency situation where the BDB database ran out of lock entries, causing some 0.7 nodes to get stuck at block 225430. Miners were advised to revert to 0.7 until the issue was resolved. In conclusion, the presence of bugs in Bitcoin upgrades highlights the importance of keeping nodes up-to-date, and miners should upgrade first if new rejection criteria are introduced. The competition for blockchain space is primarily an issue for client software which doesn't deal correctly with non-confirming transactions and misleads users.</summary>
